3rd batch POP LO. 
Good job guys! 12 weeks with you all was full of trouble. But it was a challenge to have all of you before i ORD . 
Proud of you guys af to make it to the goal i gave you all on the first day with 100% ippt passes! 0.1 % to the top of ippt scoreboard was a bonus . 
Great know most of you did not fall out on 24km üí™
Hope you all dont cause so much trouble and stop asking for smoke break. Just quit. üòâ

Late post but that day have arrive as i got back my PINK IC üòö ORD LO 
posted into tekong thinking a commander life very easy one la. NOPE it was a heck of shit . Not only i have to settle the recruits but their parent as well especially when things happen. I have to understand every recruit that is under me , so that i can train in their unique ways etc. But with all the problem and tireless times seeing them POP is my happiest moment ‚ò∫Ô∏è not because im free but because it was rewarding and parent come and thank you personally , recruits coming to you . .
.
To my 0418 & 0119 batch - you guys are the pure poly batch and pure jc batch haha training you all during PT shag me out honestly . Miss the time with you all . is really awesome to see some of you becoming commander ! Even some i work with . I guess you guys have already felt the pain being a tekong commander but still have the fire in you to bring your recruit up to where they should be no matter how shag you are like how much shit you guys cause me when you are recruits ! Jia youz and give singapore some elite soldiers. .
.
To my 0419 batch - sorry i ORD in the middle of your BMT phrase but the 2.5 months i hope you guys remember what i taught you all and continue to stay motivated thus finishing off your BMT strong ! Dont forget " a goal without action , is just a dream" See you guys only 7 dec at the float üòä .
.
To those i work with ‚ò∫Ô∏è- seriously without most of you i probably toh especially in viper , without you guys i will drown in armskote forever . You guys make life more fun to bare in both Viper and Scorpion . Miss those time haha but now most of us are civilian liaoü§∑‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è supper soon la sia . The rest i will be waiting on the other side (the civilian side) üò¨ .
.
Signing out,
3SG Joel (NS)

Words to current NSF and soon to enlist..
.
. .
. "Ai ya 2 years very fast one la üòõ"

Milestone parade ‚úÖ 
Started as a BMT recruit
End off as a BMT trainer 
Didnt started off as well in BMT  but i got all friends and family there along the way supporting me. 
Especially as a BMTC trainer in Viper company when we all started off with all new commanders and we are short handed but we all have each other backs , covering each other , bringing each other platoon to breakfast without saying. Will never forget that moment during BTP day 1 when we all counting 1000 magazine thrice in the armskote till 3 am and waking up at 5 am for day 2. 
Of course thanks for hearing my daily complain about armskote.  Thank you guys it was a pleasure serving with you all üòö
 soon we are all Sirs/Mr civilian ! 
T-7 days to ....officially ORD LO

Heard so much about New Fut Kai from my vegetarian friends and I finally had a chance to try it. @newfutkai offers Chinese vegetarian serving both traditional as well as modern fusion dishes.

@newfutkai is known for their Charcoal Hotpots, soupy mix of fresh and hearty ingredients slowly simmered over a traditional charcoal flame. You can even choose your soup base: Mushroom, Fish Head, Soy Miso, Beauty Coconut or 100 Beans.

We had some of their signatures and bestsellers such as:

Yuzhut Coconut Hotpot 
Charcoal Sesame Toufu
Mala Fish
Crispy Roast Pork 
Xing Hua Noodle (Mian Xian)

Love the Yuzhut Coconut Hotpot the most. The soup is very fragrant and flavourful with fresh ingredients. The Crispy Roast Pork is good too. You can eat it on its own or wrap it in lettuce with sauce and cucumber. I preferred it wrapped as it gives a more depth into this dish. 

It does not matter whether you‚Äôre a vegetarian or not. You should try and experience it. 

We came down on a weekend and the place is full house. Making reservation is highly recommended. Call 63980836 or make your reservation at https://
www.newfutkai.com.sg/reservations/

üìåNew Fut Kai
282 JIn Besar
Singapore 208945

üå∏Nespresso Restaurant Week Spring 2022üå∏
.
Supply & Demand Esplanade is the new addition to Nespresso Restaurant Week which is a modern Italian trattoria with a rooftop terrace and bar, known for serving up hearty pastas and delicious hand opened thin crust pizzas. 
.
Featuring the 5 Course Set Dinner ($68 per person)

STARTER
Truffle Mushroom Arancini
Scallop Crudo
Stracciatella

MAIN COURSE (Choice of 1)
Wild Caught Sea Prawn & Kombu Tagliatelle
Crab & Scallop Tagliatelle
Seared Beef Pizza
Sea Urchin Risotto +8 supplement
Miso Cod

DESSERT (Choice of 1)
Chocolate Berries Cake
Trio Of Cheese +$6 supplement

What I like here is they only use the finest and freshest ingredients. Had an honour of meeting the Chef behind their new open-concept kitchen @_wusihan_ under the pupillage of the well known French Chef Joel Robuchon. One look at his work and I can tell a story of his experience in fine dining arena. All the Starters were pretty and delicious but I fell in love with their fresh homemade Tagliatelle, super good! This is a place I want to bring my friends or family for a nice meal while enjoying the view from their rooftop terrace. 
.
Some of the above dishes were from their updated menu with the introduction of new dishes exclusive to @supplydemandsin focusing more on seasonal produce, homemade goods like fresh handmade pasta, freshly baked sourdough bread and brand-new desserts. All were proudly made in-house, headed by Chef @_wusihan_ 

You also can choose to dine or drink within the cosy interiors at the ground level with alfresco space or on the rooftop terrace overviewing the beautiful Marina Bay and Singapore‚Äôs iconic skycapers. 
.
Do give them a try and I promise you will not get disappointed!
Book your seat now @diningcitysingapore App or at www.restaurantweek.sg

[Kulto]
Another once-a-month Spanish food gathering, and this time to try @kulto.sg!

Octopus 'Galician Style' ($32)
The texture here was good! Q soft and tender, and the sauce is not bad, just that I personally prefer those that comes with a smokey or burnt flavour.

üåü Iberico Chorizo, Confit potato & Soft Eggs ($24) üì∏ 3
The chorizo was slightly smokey, and had a good bite, which also went well with the potato and runny eggs ü§§. The addition of onions was also üíØ! Oh how much I'd love to have this for breakfast regularly üòç.

Jamon Iberico Croquettes & Crab Croquettes ($14/ 4 pcs) üì∏ 4, 5
They usually sell in 4 pcs, but you can choose to get 2 of each flavour instead. Jamon Iberico tasted like carbonara in a croquette, but can't put my finger on which shop's carbonara it's similar to. For the Crab Croquette, it was really similar to the sauce used in dry laksa pasta.

üåü Homemade Cheese Terrine with Truffle & Honey Olive Oil ($22) üì∏ 6
Really creamy and light cheese that's similar to cream cheese texture. Very mild mushroom fragrance and flavour, I loved this combination! Super crispy bread to pair with too, defo enjoyable!

Charcoal Lamb Rack with Carrots & Caramelised Baby Onions ($38) üì∏ 7
The baby onions nicely helps to mask the gaminess of the lamb. The pairing sauce was slightly sour, reminding of vinegar. 

Seafood Paella (2-3 pax $39) üì∏ 2
This was literally the most hyped dish here but ended up being the most disappointing one here? The rice texture really no-go, it was pretty hard (not crispy), similar to undercooked rice. The juice from the prawn head also made it really fishy, which we didn't really enjoy. 

üåü Kulto Cheesecake ($14) üì∏ 8, 9
The cheesecake was really molten and quite creamy! The sorbet was really tangy - personally not a fan of the sorbet here, so would just go for the cheesecake. 

Whiskey Cake with Almonds ($14) üì∏ 10
Actually didn't expect them to pour whiskey over the cake, because we expected the whiskey to be infused instead. Whiskey is definitely strong and slightly spicy. Cream is really light, but reminiscent of the traditional bakery vanilla cream cake. Great for those who love whiskey!

Overall Rating: 8/10

[Milano Pizza & Wine] 
@milanopizzasg is a sister of @pastabar_sg, and I was really excited to finally book a seat to try it!

Sicilian Grandma Pizzas (6" square, 2" deep pie):
Let's first talk about the dough - their Grandma Pizzas use sourdough, so it's slightly tangy in flavour. I'd say it's really unique, with it being slightly thick, crispy on the outside and slightly airy on the inside! 

Mortadella & Burrata ($27++)
This was probably my favourite that night! We had 1-2 pizzas before this, so I really loved how the burrata helped to cut through some of the greasiness with its light and creamy flavour. The mortadella isn't strong unlike meats like Parma ham, so you don't get to taste much of the meat as a whole.

Truffle Mushroom ($38++)
This came with truffle cream and fresh shaved truffle, but you only get a slight hint of truffle. Expected it to be really strong, but the mixed mushrooms are instead more overpowering. Personally would prefer even stronger truffle flavour, but those who love mushroom flavours more would prefer this.

Neo-Neopolitan 12" Pizzas:
Beef Cheek Bolognese ($34++) üì∏ 4
Slow-simmered beef cheek. Felt that their neopolitan pizza doughs are slightly tougher, especially once it cools a little. 

Sausage & Hot Chilies ($28++) üì∏ 5
Homemade pork sausage is used here, and comes with pickled hot chillies. Didn't remember this to be spicy tho!

Korea town ($32++) üì∏ 6
You do taste Korean flavours, which comes from the Gochujang & kimchi. Overall decent pizza, except some slices of the Marinated Short Rib were really chewy and almost impossible to bite through (we were guessing tendon?).

Desserts:
Amalfi Lemon Meringue Pie ($16++)
This was good! The lemon was surprisingly not really tangy, and the pie was of the flaky kind with layers similar to millefeuille. Overall paired with the basil cream, this was q a delight to have.

Tiramisu Pie ($16++)
I tried this before the lemon meringue, and I really liked the tiramisu flavour! But this really took the backseat once I had the lemon meringue pie.
The pie here was quite dry and didn't have much flavour - wouldn't mind to remove the pie entirely, and just serve tiramisu üòÇ.

Overall Rating: 7/10

[90 Minutes] - Tasting
For those who love Korean Hotpot, here's one affordable option near Dhoby Ghaut MRT!

For 90 minutes, you get to enjoy buffet with free flow soft drinks! You also get to pick the sauce for your hotpot - we got Classic (Homemade + Gungjung) & Rose (Carbonara + Volcano).

Add-ons:

[Don Lechon]
Have you tried Filipino food before? I've had decent ones previously, and this place was pretty famous for their pork, so I was really excited to head down to try it.

You can choose to get rice meals/ order dishes ala carte here, but the former will come with rice and smaller portion of meat that's more suitable for 1 pax.

Lechon Sisig Ala Carte ($14)
This was the better of the 2 dishes. It's meant to be piping hot when served, but it only sizzled for a good 15s before it stopped, which was pretty disappointing. The meat here was quite flavourful and went well with rice, but it's apparently meant to be crispier. (Swipe to 3rd üì∏ for sizzle)

Chopped Lechon (0.5kg - $22, 1kg - $40)
I came here for these, but these were served cold, which already meant what we were having weren't of the best quality. Some pieces of skin were crispy, but there were some that were very hard and almost impossible to bite through. There's nothing special about the pork here as well other than its thick cut.

Overall pretty disappointing, and after being hyped for such a long time, I guess the standards have really dropped drastically.

Overall Rating: 5/10

[Spacebox] - Invited Tasting
@spaceboxsg has really interesting Space-themed bistro bar vibes, and are great for those who love to drink and enjoy loklok/ zichar dishes there!

Assorted Skewers
Their broccoli is a must-try! Really well-grilled with that charred/ smoky flavour. There's q a good variety of meat skewers (pork, beef, lamb, chicken), as well as meatball, crabmeat, lotus root and Taiwan Sausage!

Grilled Scallops (Garlic/ Cheese)
I liked the generous amount of cheese used for their scallops, and the ÂÜ¨Á≤â (glass noodles) used for the garlic one was pretty flavourful too!

Moonlight Hor Fun
This was a little similar to having CKT, but not that I mind it, because it's again flavourful, and the noodles are q well-cooked, so definitely enjoyable!

Yang Zhou Fried Rice
This fried rice isn't the kind with strong wokhei, but it's more of comforting, hearty ones which some may enjoy too.

Ëæ£Â≠êÈ∏° Szechuan Spicy Chicken 
Although this wasn't spicy at all, I personally really liked the strong spice flavours, which was enough to keep me going at it.

Roast Pork with Garlic
I really liked this dish?! Really soft and tender pork, which was pretty flavourful too. For those who love garlic, you can pair their pork with an entire garlic clove, which definetely will pack a huge GARLIC punch, and best part is the garlic skin was really crispy! 

Enoki Mushroom
It's not extremely strong on the butter or garlic in the sauce here, but it's still pretty enjoyable with a good bite in the sauce that it's cooked in!

If you're up for some veg, there's also Sambal Lady's Fingers which aren't really spicy, and Ê≤πÈ∫¶Ëèú (Chinese Lettuce) that was surprisingly q enjoyable too!

Thank you @fatpigdiary for inviting and @spaceboxsg for hosting!

Set lunch ($148)
‚≠êÔ∏è 4/5 ‚≠êÔ∏è
üç¥Gastronomic French fine dining experience by Chef Jason showcasing Gastro-Botanica 2.0 - a menu highlighting botanical elements of vegetables, tubers, herbs, spices, and fruits. The food was certainly well-executed, with every dish a medley of delicious flavours. That said, the starters and mains didn‚Äôt quite take our breath away, with us only experiencing true euphoria with the dessert. 

Started with mochishire, a cheesy mochi-like chewy bread. These lightly aromatic bread were addictive and we had to stop ourselves from asking for more! It was paired with a light tomato-based sauce that enhanced the cheesy flavour. 

Amuse bouche were 1) refreshing watermelon radish, 2) rich gorgonzola black truffle, and 3) feuille de brick (i.e., best described as elevated CNY snack with caviar). 

For the mains, we had tender hamachi that sat in a delightful sauce made from dill, coconut, green chilli, and cashew. Next was fresh Hokkaido scallops paired with artichoke done in 3 ways and chicken oysters in a light yet savory sauce. Main was succulent Iberico pork with melt-in-the-mouth foie gras.

The dessert was the star for its perfectly balanced sweet-savory balance. Smooth Hokkaido milk panna cotta, aromatic ginger flower, strawberry consume, thai basil oil, and legume essence from red onion and kombu. Ended off with Alice in Wonderland (petite four) - Horlick kinako mochi, Canele, Macademia, Nutmeg Madeline.

How do words even begin to convey the sadness I feel right now?

I still walk past your room and peek in, hoping to see you there. I heard the sound of your bell that you used to call me with and I instinctively rushed over over hoping to see you there, but it was an accidental press by a family member changing the bedsheets after you left. 

I‚Äôll miss the days where we shared a slice of strawberry shortcake, the days where you would pretend to steal my fries knowing I‚Äôll give it to you anyways, our yearly trip to the zoo and more recently flower dome. I‚Äôll miss cutting your hair, beard and nails because you didn‚Äôt want to go out anymore in the past two years. I‚Äôll miss buying you your favourite foods and supper every night and sitting on the couch sharing a persimmon together.

You are dearly and tremendously missed, my favourite person. I hope you are happy in heaven, free from pain, and eating as much orh luat and chilli crab as you can. Till we meet again üíî

My arteries are gonna scream at this decadence. 

Presenting the roadkill crew of a fullpacker brisket that i naively butchered into multiple bits. I can totally imagine having this whole, fat bits on flat, if i hadnt been so over zealous with the carving knife. 

Documenting the hours so i can remind my dory brain the arduous work that goes into doing an overnight smoke whenever excitement supercedes reality again.

Total 17hours jarrah wood smoked
First 3 hours - 110c
Next 3 hours was left simmering with whatever heat that was left since the bed consumed me
(Thank God for constant tropical heat)
6 hours - unwrapped 120c
5 hours - wrapped in butcher paper at 150c
2 hours rest

All in all, a job well done. Tastetest fam was well pleased. Good job smoke mama.

With the school holidays coming up in a couple of weeks, why not try making these nutritious and delicious Kabocha Beef Croquettes for your kiddos at home? Or even better, get them to do it with you!

Thank you @she_wan for contributing such a versatile and easy recipe.‚ù£Ô∏è

You‚Äôll need:
500g kabocha (jap pumpkin, or substitute with butternut squash / reg pumpkin), cubed
250g Huber‚Äôs minced beef
1 pc yellow onion, minced
3 pcs garlic cloves, grated
1 tbsp parsley or chives, chiffonade
2 slices provolone cheese, cubed
1/2 cup parmigiano reggiano, freshly grated

1 cup plain flour
2 eggs, beatened
2 cups panko breadcrumbs

Method:
1) Boil or steam kabocha.

2) Saut√© onion and garlic until softened.

3) Strain kabocha well and mash. It is important to remove any excess liquid.

4) Add all ingredients into a large bowl and mix well. Season with salt and pepper.

5) Form into croquette shape patties and let it rest and cook for 15 minutes. You may place them in the freezer briefly to make it easier to coat later.

6) Coat croquettes in flour, egg mixture then panko.

6) Deep fry until golden brown, approx. 4 minutes. You may also bake or air fry the croquettes, simply spray with oil before baking.

Enjoy hot! They are crunchy on the outside, moist and soft on the inside. ü§§

P.S. The mixture can be shaped into bite sized balls making them great for parties and addition to bento boxes too!

Thank you @fragrance_bak_kwa for sending these snacks over! 

I haven‚Äôt tried all the snacks but for the ones I‚Äôve tried heres what I think: 

I was rly impressed by the crispy bak kwa which tasted like bak kwa chips. I would dare say that crispy bak kwa is superior to the original chewy bak kwa. The texture somehow works! Its a scarily addictive snack and my fam ate it all in one day 8/10

The pork floss was p good too! The best way to eat pork floss is not in porridge‚Ä¶. I like mine stuffed in between two slices of soft bread that have been smothered in cream cheese‚Ä¶ The slight sweetness of the cream cheese goes well w the savoury crunchy pork floss. It sounds rly bad but trust me!! This combi works :‚Äù) 8/10

The truffle potato chips were q interesting‚Ä¶. The chips themselves were p thick. The seasoning was q confusing?? bc it was truffle+salted egg yolk. It didnt help that the seasoning caked each indi chip!! Wasnt my fav but the chips still went down p quickly 6/10

üìçNeptune 

Grana Panado Scones with yuzu jam, honey mascarpone and cold salmon & shrimp in dill sauce. (8/10)

The scones were p buttery and the scallion flav came through quite nicely! The yuzu jam paired well with the savoury scone and was my fav condiment of the 3! The honey mascarpone did not taste like honey so it was p meh‚Ä¶ my friend thought the shrimp & salmon dill sauce was good though! Personally, I‚Äôm not a seafood fan haha but ig if you like poke you wld like it! :) Paid $17 eeks so its not v worth it :((

üìçPark Bench Deli 
PBD Big Breakfast (7/10)
I was really looking forward to trying the mini ricotta hotcakes but maybe I overhyped them for myself. The hotcakes were fluffy but tasted of old oil‚Ä¶.also, they were heavily doused in sweet syrup (probably not maple syrup) bc they tasted exactly like mac‚Äôs hotcakes üò© the tater tots were good though! they had a mild spicy seasoning on them! Scrambled eggs were soft but again‚Ä¶ were doused in the same macs syrup which I wasn‚Äôt a big fan of 

Hot Honey Chicken (9/10) 
this sandwich made an otherwise disappointing trip to PBD slightly better! the chicken was crispy on the outside and super juicy on the inside üò≠ It went rly well with the brown butter hot honey as well as the basil mayo. I liked how the lettuce added some needed freshness to the sandwich. Pickles & cheddar didnt rly add much value imo haha but overall a rly good fried chicken sandwich and wld come back for it

üìçAtlas Coffeehouse 

Wurst Rosti (7/10) 
Unfortunately the Rosti was slightly oily and abit burnt‚Ä¶ but the rest of the components were cooked well and complemented the crispy potato pancake. I particularly liked the tomato chutney which added a nice acidity to a somewhat heavy and oily dish! 

Granola, Pears and Yogurt (7.5/10) 
The tea poached pears elevated an otherwise boring granola bowl! I liked how the pears were naturally sweet and paired nicely with the tart yogurt and crunchy granola. It was rather small for $13.90 though

My lovely, dear friend @iryna.khorobrova gave me a calendar for Women‚Äôs Day many years ago with these stunning images. I saved it and bring it out for my class each year to see the beautiful art. This post from  @aestheticsofjoy made me feel hopeful and tearful. We must #standwithukraine 
„Éª„Éª„Éª
Repost: I first discovered these extraordinary flower crowns, called vinok, when I was researching JOYFUL. üå∏ They‚Äôre the perfect marriage of abundance and renewal aesthetics, a traditional Ukrainian art form that has been revived in recent years by @third_roosters.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
I thought of them today when I checked the news. War flattens our understanding of people. It makes them into victims or soldiers or heroes. We celebrate their fierceness, but we see only one side of their humanity.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
Art can‚Äôt save lives, but it dimensionalizes people. Joy can‚Äôt stop bombs, but it helps remind us what‚Äôs at stake. Not just territory, not just self-government, but the vibrancy of culture, traditions, history, festivity, community, LIFE.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
When I see these images I feel a renewed flush of anger that these people are fighting for their lives, when they could be making art.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
üì∏: @third_roosters

And also, I think by now, my friends are used to me not replying their messages on time üòÖüòÇ (Right now, some of them are probably thinking why I haven't texted back, when I've time to post on ig...hahaha üòÜ) 

Lastly, I just wanted to say that there have been many cases in Singapore, and some people around me are worried about testing positive after doing the ART test etc. üòï I know it can get really stressful at work/school/home etc. Really hope the situation gets better real soon. 

So just wanted to send love to all üíïüíïüíï

Hope everyone's doing alright! üôÇüôÇ
Happy sweet Sunday!

AWARE x UNREAL (Link in bio)

As we battle the COVID19 pandemic, some have suffered much more than others. Singapore has seen a 112% spike in domestic violence, many of whom are afraid to speak out or antagonize their abusers.

The Association of Women for Action and Research (AWARE) is the leading gender equality advocacy organization. AWARE supports & empowers women, seeking to remove all gender-based barriers that prevent them from developing their full potential & realizing their hopes & dreams. It does this in three ways; research & advocacy, education, and providing social services.

This Saturday (31 October 2020), our very own UNREAL trainers will be walking "A Mile In Her Shoes" - yes, one mile...in heels! If you'd like to come down to support them, the walk kicks off at 0730 at Republic Plaza & the boys will be walking to Victoria Concert Hall ü§≠

An event organised by Luxequisite x AWARE, UNREAL is happy to play a part in this meaningful campaign & we hope that you will support this as well by donating through this link - https://www.giving.sg/campaigns/a_mile_in_her_shoes_x_unreal_personal_training

Had a gastronomical experience at At Twenty, where Chef Chef Shunsuke Kusubashi had exquisitely executed the premium ingredients from Ishikawa, Kochi and Okinawa ‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è

A quick introduction to the three states in Japan, Ishikawa is known for their fresh seafood from its abundant fishing grounds. Some of the highlights from Ishikawa which include flying squid, agodashi and Aperitif (umeshu sparkling wine). 

Whereas Kochi prefecture is blessed with clean water and a variety of vegetables like high quality tomatoes, eggplant and Sakura syrup.

Boosting nutrient-rich land and pure seawater, Okinawa produced a number of first-rate ingredients. You can get natural sea salt, prawn, mango, brown sugar and Shikuwasa.

Here we have a beautiful petite weevil from the forest floor, a flightless rainforest litter species with moss growth all over its back! Its species is identified by Joshua @tenebrionid.fan , tentatively Acicnemis cf. sp.

The association seems to involve symbiosis, with the weevils providing a favourable environment for the plants, and the plants endowing the weevils with a protective resemblance to cryptogram-covered parts of plants, or with chemical protection. Thanks @sgbeetlenut for the article. GRESSITT, J., SAMUELSON, G. & VITT, D. Moss growing on Living Papuan Moss-forest Weevils. Nature 217, 765‚Äì767 (1968).

A large, spectacular notodontid - Dudusa synopla from the submontane forests of Peninsula Malaysia. When agitated, it bends the abdomen forward in the manner of a scorpion. I've read that the urticating hairs on the tail could cause skin irritations.

Borneo has a group of miniature frogs called the genus Pelophryne (Dwarf Toads), they can be really small in size reaching the max size of 3.8cm. Their toe pads are extended and flat, making them look adorable as they walk slowly. The species depicted in the picture is P. saravacensis, a species found in the highlands of Sarawak. Along the same trail, I saw many other Ansonia minuta while searching for the famed Rainbow Toad.

One of the largest katydids in my life (I haven't seen many actually, still in the progress), it took awhile to get this ID-ed but I managed to consult with Chien Lee, my inspiration. As of now, its genus is in a need of revision, so it could be either undescribed or described in a species complex! Pseudophyllus sp. 

It was found 2.5 metres above ground on a coniferous tree.

So.. I have been struggling with severe depression over the last 2 years and it really hasn't been easy. I used to think that it was all in the head, that it was something I could control. From hurting and slicing parts of my body, to attempted suicide by overdose a couple times(really almost died once). Turns out, the longer I let it fester the worse it got, symptoms started showing up around age 20 but I always brushed it off. So I have learnt to take mental health very seriously. Over the last couple months I have been doing much better with the help of my loving  fianc√©e, supportive family, friends(you know who you are) , my awesome team at work. Very thankful and grateful for that. I wouldn't replace them for anything in the world. 
So long story short, since I have been doing better, what's left that reminds me of the very dark days are the scars I have on me, thus I have decided to get it covered up to close up that dark chapter of my life and move on to greater things! This piece done by @kennethalchemytattoo is not simply a tattoo, it actually helped me close up that dark chapter, thank you Kenneth for this beautiful work. 

Do take your mental health seriously everyone! Everyone can fall prey to it if you aren't careful and always think that it's all in the mind, wish everyone reading this post well! üôè The mind controls the body, never forget that!

29 <feb highlights>
I‚Äôve apologised for being here & then apologised for leaving. Always feeling like i shouldn‚Äôt be in this team/class/office/group of friends.. Periodically confessing in a form of a joke about how i didnt ask to be here. At some point, minimised my presence by furthering a terrible slouch, i didnt want to show up. It felt like so much work - breathing

It felt so unfair to exist, how painful it is to live because i never consented to this. How i viewed a birthday as a celebration no, not for me, for mum! Cuz she raised me (which is still true nonetheless) and it was all her effort (its not all hers anymore üòå)

The past few months however, i put in so much fucking effort to make breathing feel less laborious for myself (ironically). Finding my values, fully aligning to them, detaching my worth from a status, job, income, shit i post, friendship & learning how to be happy/content just being in my own skin. (Fyi, healthy individuals, its a lot of work ok) 

I‚Äôm still learning..how to navigate.. How to unabashedly ask for what i want or clarify tension.. How to be a supportive friend, partner, sister, daughter, cousin, niece etc AND even if i fall short, i‚Äôll be upset, but my world wouldnt burn to the ground

I dont know how i‚Äôll feel next month or even next week lol, but at least i know today, i celebrate life, love and growth!! Today breathing feels easier. Happy birthday me üíì i wouldnt be here without you ALL (u noe hu u r) for supporting me in this trajectory. Thank u
thankful for the mindful and grounded energy üíì

JANUARY opened with its uninhibited relational experiences (that i hold close to heart). I had a lot of fun and the theme carried through the month. It‚Äôs been about being honest with new relationships im keen on establishing and whom (i think) care enough about me. It‚Äôs been about being honest with myself with my underlying reasons for anxiety and procrastination for action. About leaning into that inner voice I‚Äôve smothered for so long that tells me if I‚Äôm doing too much or okay to expend more because i can! I would like to carry this trust forward in the next few months

Having a foundation of love (for those who dk me, i dont mean romantic love) regardless of where i am physically in life (aka job, housing, etc) helps me love myself & find my worth. Strangely, being capitalistically not so valuable can bring out more value within yourself in that sense. Importance of being interdependent. People who love you for you when udk how to, while you learn to love yourself. Kinda like training wheels

Also had the opportunity to compare my environment from before & who i prefer to surround myself with today. I am so insanely blessed with my preferred company (i hope they like me back)

I‚Äôm sensing February to be slightly more chaotic and that‚Äôs okay üòä Recapping Jan like this because the internet says like attracts like and i want to manifest this healing energy. Who m i to distrust the internet
I‚Äôm on my own timeline!! I‚Äôm wholly created!!! The journey is uniquely mine!!!! Focus pocus

Avocado Toast is delicious. But it is also one of the most overpriced and overhyped cafe dishes. This is the way that my fianc√© and I make our guacamole occasionally on weekends. Easy but absolutely delicious. You can try it for yourself!

1. Cut an avocado and put in a bowl then mash with a fork
2. Season with salt and black pepper
3. Mince 1 small shallot and add to the bowl
4. Chop about 6 cherry tomatoes for 1 avocado and transfer to the bowl
5. Chop as much cilantro as you like and mix everything together
6. To finish, add small cubes of avocado and lemon juice and adjust to taste if needed
7. Serve on toasted bread

Who doesn't love a good meat sandwich. Slivers of beautifully smoked meat stuffed between two slices of bread, with the meat stack being thicker than the slices of bread. 

Pastrami sandwiches are oftened served using rye bread, with mustard and pickles. I decided to give the sandwich a slight Japanese twist because I really wanted to make 'Sunomono' using Japanese cucumbers for my pickles. I also mixed some shiro miso into my hot English mustard for a touch of fermented saltiness. Unfortunately, I couldn't get my hands on rye bread, so I used sourdough instead. Nonetheless, it was a very gratifying meal. 

For today's loose recipe, I will be touching more on the condiments. The mustard and the pickles. I got my pastrami from @bellyhappychef but you could use or buy other smoked meats to your liking.

ùêâùêöùê©ùêöùêßùêûùê¨ùêû ùêÇùêÆùêúùêÆùê¶ùêõùêûùê´ 'ùêíùêÆùêßùê®ùê¶ùê®ùêßùê®'
1. Finely slice Japanese cucumber with a mandoline
2. Salt the cucumber for 1 hour and drain out the excess water
3. Marinade with soya sauce, shredded kombu, a touch of sugar and rice vinegar 
4. Set aside and use it when needed
5. For myself, I added a tablespoon of furikake to the marinade for a slight savoury taste

ùêáùê®ùê≠ ùêåùê¢ùê¨ùê® ùêåùêÆùê¨ùê≠ùêöùê´ùêù
1. Use English mustard or if you want, horseradish for that kick
2. Mix white miso in a little hot water till it "dissolves" and let it cool
3. Mix the miso into the mustard slowly
4. The water is meant to loosen and cut down on the sharpness of the mustard

Prawns are seriously such a versatile ingredients and can be cooked in a multitude of ways. Typically I remove the heads to concentrate the flavour of the prawns in some sort of oil or stock. Today is not that day. This dish features the whole prawn, prepared really simply. 

The sea glass prawns from @lyhseafood were super fresh and juicy. What better way to serve them than just simply steamed with tons of garlic. I've added a few extra elements along the way but feel free to keep it as simple as you want! 

ùêàùêßùê¨ùê≠ùê´ùêÆùêúùê≠ùê¢ùê®ùêßùê¨
1. Cut down the back of the prawn to devein it and to butterfly the prawn
2. In a bowl mix together light soya sauce, grated garlic, shaoxing wine and sesame oil
3. Marinate your prawns for about 20 minutes
4. Make a small cornflour slurry using about 1 tsp of corn flour with 3 tbsp of water
5. Mix the slurry with 1 egg white and about 1 tbsp of the marinade 
6. Layer the prawns in a steaming dish and pour the egg white mixture at the bottom
7. Arrange the prawns on the dish and top it generously with finely minced garlic and a few slices of ginger
8. Steam for 5 to 10 mins depending on the size of your prawns
9. Serve directly from the steaming dish and add coriander and spring onions for garnish

I wasn't planning to cook steak over the weekend but when you are nearby a place like @foodiemarketplacesg it would be silly not to. Reflecting on today's photo, it definitely is different from my usual style tone-wise. Come to think of it, even after years of posting, I don't think I've arrived at a particular style. But I digress.

I bought a nice piece of Argentinian Flat Iron beef. The flat iron is a cut of meat that isn't a prime cut. But by removing the sinew in the right way, it is perfectly tender with a slight chew. It is actually one of my favourite cuts of steak! To go with the steak, I made a peppercorn sauce. 

Making a good steak sauce is a great lesson in patience and concentrating flavours. There aren't too many ingredients but, without the correct technique, the sauce can turn out vastly different. Typically a pan sauce (sauce made directly in the steak pan), I prefer to make it separately and then add in the resting juices after to keep the flavour cleaner and to reduce burnt and bitter notes when searing a steak. If you are curious how I made it, check out the loose recipe! 

ùêàùêßùê¨ùê≠ùê´ùêÆùêúùê≠ùê¢ùê®ùêßùê¨
1. Slice shallots and garlic in a pan
2. Add a knob of butter and 1 tbsp of olive oil to gently cook the ingredients
3. Add a handful of assorted peppercorns (I used mainly black and pink) and a few sprigs of thyme
4. When the onion start to caramelise, giving off a light brown colour, add cognac  and cook off the alcohol 
5. Once the cognac is almost fully reduced 
6. Add in beef stock and reduce by more than half
7. For the final step add in cream to taste and texture and bring to a boil then off the heat
8. Add in crushed peppercorns and stir through
9. After resting your steak, pour in the resting juices into the sauce. You might need to heat up the sauce and reduce the liquid a little. 

ùêÑùê±ùê≠ùê´ùêö ùêìùê¢ùê©ùê¨
1. Cognac has a high alcohol %. If you are going to flamb√©, do it away from the direct heat source 
2. The sugars from the alcohol and onions when caramelizing helps in part to give the sauce a more glossy appeal
